Objective
Unbreak the display: get the maze rendering again with the HUD visible but not blocking, then lock in a safe layering pattern so this doesn’t regress.

What likely happened
- The new HUD/styles are sitting “on top” of the canvas (full-bleed absolute block or opaque background), or canvas sizing got zeroed by CSS so the renderer is painting to a 0×0 surface. Both yield “HUD shows, maze is gone.”

Moves happening now
- I pulled our prior session history to locate the two games (maze-forest and narrative-maze-prototype) and the recent HUD/renderer work. This looks like a layering/sizing regression, not a logic one.

Immediate hotfix (safe to apply now)
Apply these three minimal changes to Maze Forest. They preserve your new visuals but guarantee the canvas paints and the HUD doesn’t occlude it.

1) Ensure DOM structure and ids (maze-forest/index.html)
- Wrap the canvas and HUD in a positioned root. Keep the canvas before the HUD.

<div id="gameRoot">
  <canvas id="game" width="960" height="960"></canvas>
  <!-- keep HUD after canvas so z-index works predictably -->
  <div id="hudTL" aria-hidden="false">
    <!-- existing HUD content -->
  </div>
</div>

2) Fix layering and pointer-events (maze-forest/styles.css)
Add or update these rules — names can coexist with your current CSS.

#gameRoot {
  position: relative;
  width: 960px;            /* or 100% if you responsive-scale both */
  margin: 0 auto;
}
#game {
  display: block;
  width: 960px;            /* match #gameRoot width or use 100% in sync */
  height: 960px;           /* square so renderer grid fits */
  z-index: 1;
}
#hudTL {
  position: absolute;
  top: 12px;
  left: 12px;
  z-index: 2;
  pointer-events: none;    /* never block keyboard or canvas clicks */
  background: transparent; /* make certain it can’t cover the board */
}
#hudTL :is(button, a, input, [role="button"]) {
  pointer-events: auto;    /* if HUD has interactive bits */
}

If you used any global reset like #hudTL { position: fixed; inset: 0; }, delete it or scope it to narrative only.

3) Lock canvas sizing at runtime (maze-forest/src/renderer.js)
Make sure we size the backing store and reset transform. This avoids “drawing to zero” when CSS scales.

const canvas = document.getElementById('game');
const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');

function fitCanvasToCSS() {
  const dpr = Math.max(1, window.devicePixelRatio || 1);
  const cssW = Math.floor(canvas.clientWidth);
  const cssH = Math.floor(canvas.clientHeight);
  if (!cssW || !cssH) return; // bail if hidden; next tick will catch it
  canvas.width = cssW * dpr;
  canvas.height = cssH * dpr;
  ctx.setTransform(dpr, 0, 0, dpr, 0, 0);
}

window.addEventListener('resize', fitCanvasToCSS);
setTimeout(fitCanvasToCSS, 0); // after CSS/layout settles
fitCanvasToCSS();

If your draw loop previously setTransform every frame, remove that duplicate to avoid compounding transforms.

Approvals needed
- If this regression is in Maze Forest, I propose we keep the original Maze Forest HUD and scope the new “top-left cozy HUD” only to Narrative for now to reduce cross-game CSS clashes. Approve scoping? Yes/No.
- If this is actually the Narrative build, same fix applies — but I’ll also gate HUD CSS under body[data-game="narrative"] to prevent global leakage. Approve? Yes/No.

Minimal confirmation I need
- Which game is broken: Maze Forest or Narrative Prototype?
- If you have a local URL/path you’re using (e.g., http://localhost:8000/maze-forest/index.html), paste it so I target the right index.html.

Next checkpoint
- After you apply the snippet (or approve me to patch), reload:
  - Expect: canvas paints the maze, HUD sits top-left, keyboard works, no overlay blocking.
- Then I’ll:
  - Scope the cozy HUD CSS to narrative only, or finish the Maze Forest HUD port properly without global styles.
  - Gate diagnostics for “ship” mode so we don’t carry debug overlays.

Operator update — What advanced, risks, next
- Advanced: Isolated the failure class (overlay/sizing). Provided concrete DOM/CSS/runtime fixes you can drop in immediately.
- Risks: Any global CSS (e.g., fixed full-viewport HUD or resets targeting canvas) can reintroduce the issue if not scoped. I’ll namespace HUD styles per game after your confirmation.
- Next: Tell me which game instance is broken and approve CSS scoping. I’ll commit the patch and return with a verified, gated build.

